==Old English==

===Etymology===
Via Germanic, from the Indo-European base ''*bhendh-'' ‘bind’.  Cognate with Old High German [[bintan]] (German [[binden]]), Old Norse [[binda]] (Swedish [[binda]]), Middle Low German ''binden'' (Dutch [[binden]]).  The IE root was also the source of Avestan ''bendayaiti'' and Greek {{polytonic|[[πεῖσμα]]}}.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'bɪndan/}}

===Verb===
'''bindan''' (strong verb class III: '''bindeþ'''/'''bint''' ‘he binds’; '''band''' ‘he bound’; '''bundon''' ‘they bound’; past participle '''ġebunden''')
# to [[bind]], [[constrain]]
# to [[fasten]] or [[join]]

